00:13:15,330 --> 00:13:16,470
It's not just a little widget

281
00:13:16,470 --> 00:13:18,510
inside of a plain vanilla server.

282
00:13:18,510 --> 00:13:21,783
The entire widget is a
validated FIPS module.

283
00:13:22,980 --> 00:13:25,020
But there are some alternatives

284
00:13:25,020 --> 00:13:27,780
that will be relevant for your customers.

285
00:13:27,780 --> 00:13:29,460
I mentioned earlier that
the original definition

286
00:13:29,460 --> 00:13:32,310
of BYOK allowed for imported key material.

287
00:13:32,310 --> 00:13:36,060
We call this an imported
CMK, where the CMK,

288
00:13:36,060 --> 00:13:39,090
the construct, exists at the KMS API,

289
00:13:39,090 --> 00:13:41,943
but the key material is
injected by the customer.

290
00:13:43,320 --> 00:13:44,617
Some customers came to us and said,

291
00:13:44,617 --> 00:13:49,260
"Well I can't quite convince everybody

292
00:13:49,260 --> 00:13:52,020
that a multi-tenant HSM is a good idea.

293
00:13:52,020 --> 00:13:54,570
I think it is and I'm
an expert in this stuff.

294
00:13:54,570 --> 00:13:55,500
But sometimes people are like,

295
00:13:55,500 --> 00:13:57,350
what do you mean a multi-tenant HSM?"

296
00:13:58,287 --> 00:13:59,120
And so we offered an alternative.

297
00:13:59,120 --> 00:14:00,960
We have a cloud HSM product

298
00:14:00,960 --> 00:14:03,180
that is in fact a single tenant HSM

299
00:14:03,180 --> 00:14:07,470
and you can graft that thing
