306
00:14:22,710 --> 00:14:24,120
We built another thing

307
00:14:24,120 --> 00:14:26,620
that we're sure we don't
think anybody should use,

308
00:14:28,770 --> 00:14:31,230
but we built it because
customers demanded it of us,

309
00:14:31,230 --> 00:14:34,260
which is practically the
reason we build anything.

310
00:14:34,260 --> 00:14:36,603
And that's called XKS,
the external key store.

311
00:14:37,710 --> 00:14:40,800
This allows for sometimes
what you will hear

312
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:45,603
referred to as HYOK, hold your own key.

313
00:14:47,100 --> 00:14:48,780
The cool part about
the cloud is that we do

314
00:14:48,780 --> 00:14:53,780
all of the impossible part,
from the ground to the concrete,

315
00:14:53,910 --> 00:14:57,783
to locking the doors at night,
all the way up to the stack.

316
00:14:58,920 --> 00:15:03,150
Some customers, whether
because the requirement

317
00:15:03,150 --> 00:15:04,960
is placed upon them by a third party

318
00:15:05,850 --> 00:15:08,790
or because there's somebody
in the security org

319
00:15:08,790 --> 00:15:11,943
that needs a warm blanket,
which is an okay reason,

320
00:15:13,050 --> 00:15:15,390
believe that that key
needs to live in a building

321
00:15:15,390 --> 00:15:16,860
that they control.

322
00:15:16,860 --> 00:15:18,930
It needs to be in my house.

323
00:15:18,930 --> 00:15:22,113
Like all right, we'll
build it and we built it.

324
00:15:23,430 --> 00:15:24,780
This allows you to have an HSM

325
00:15:24,780 --> 00:15:26,640
that lives in your own office building

326
00:15:26,640 --> 00:15:29,250
but is hooked up to the front end of KMS

327
00:15:29,250 --> 00:15:30,453
and that's called XKS.

328
00:15:31,620 --> 00:15:33,990
Probably don't let people do this.

329
00:15:33,990 --> 00:15:35,700
It comes with scaling,

330
00:15:35,700 --> 00:15:37,830
it comes with availability characteristics

331
00:15:37,830 --> 00:15:39,930
that are gonna be radically different

332
00:15:39,930 --> 00:15:43,170
than good old regular KMS
where we do the scaling

333
00:15:43,170 --> 00:15:44,550
and the availability for you.

334
00:15:44,550 --> 00:15:45,720
But it is out there.

335
00:15:45,720 --> 00:15:50,460
But the good news is as you
build to integrate it with KMS,

336
00:15:50,460 --> 00:15:53,490
your customers still get
all this flexibility.

337
00:15:53,490 --> 00:15:55,020
That you yourself as the ISV,

338
00:15:55,020 --> 00:15:57,720
don't really need a
reason about this part,

339
00:15:57,720 --> 00:15:59,970
but it will be relevant
for the conversation.

340
00:16:01,740 --> 00:16:04,083
So let's do a quick primer.

341
00:16:05,490 --> 00:16:08,010
I think a lot of people think
they know what encryption is,

342
00:16:08,010 --> 00:16:11,103
but as it turns out, encrypting
data is the easy part.

343
00:16:12,240 --> 00:16:15,280
All you gotta do is combine
a data key with data

344
00:16:16,140 --> 00:16:19,200
and then you get ciphered
data, encrypted data.

345
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:21,093
That is categorically the easy part.

346
00:16:22,050 --> 00:16:24,150
That's what you're probably already doing.

347
00:16:24,150 --> 00:16:26,700
But the problem is what do
I do with this data key?

348
00:16:27,900 --> 00:16:31,023
Where do I put it? How do
I keep it safe over time?

349
00:16:32,072 --> 00:16:35,370
And the answer is that
you combine that data key

350
00:16:35,370 --> 00:16:37,860
with another key and you encrypt

351
00:16:37,860 --> 00:16:40,200
the key with a different key.

352
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:43,440
This is known as wrapping.
Wrapping like a present.

353
00:16:43,440 --> 00:16:46,470
So you're gonna wrap that
data key with the KMS key

354
00:16:46,470 --> 00:16:48,663
and now you have an encrypted data key.

355
00:16:49,680 --> 00:16:51,840
So where do you store that?

356
00:16:51,840 --> 00:16:53,049
Well, as it turns out, the right place

357
00:16:53,049 --> 00:16:55,073
to store it is just store
it with the encrypted data.

358
00:16:56,490 --> 00:16:58,860
You store the data encryption key,

359
00:16:58,860 --> 00:17:01,140
I'm gonna start calling that a DEK.

360
00:17:01,140 --> 00:17:03,120
You store the DEK wrapped with the top key

361
00:17:03,120 --> 00:17:06,450
that lives in KMS and
you put it in one package

362
00:17:06,450 --> 00:17:08,600
and then you put it
somewhere safe like S3.

363
00:17:10,350 --> 00:17:13,090
The question is, "Well you told me Pete

364
00:17:14,550 --> 00:17:15,870
start with the DEK.

365
00:17:15,870 --> 00:17:17,280
You got a data encryption key,

366
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:19,290
then you gotta protect
that with another key.

367
00:17:19,290 --> 00:17:21,600
Great. Is it turtles all the way down.

368
00:17:21,600 --> 00:17:23,280
What do I do with the KMS key?"

369
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:25,530
And that's where we come
in. We do the rest of it.

370
00:17:25,530 --> 00:17:26,490
And if you wanna learn about

371
00:17:26,490 --> 00:17:30,000
all the full key hierarchy of
KMS, you can find that online.

372
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:32,010
It's actually a pretty interesting story.

373
00:17:32,010 --> 00:17:33,990
We take care of all that other hard part.

374
00:17:33,990 --> 00:17:38,790
And of course we protect
your KMS keys at rest

375
00:17:38,790 --> 00:17:39,930
by encrypting them again.

376
00:17:39,930 --> 00:17:41,070
And then there's a whole thing

377
00:17:41,070 --> 00:17:43,380
and it kind of is
turtles all the way down,

378
00:17:43,380 --> 00:17:47,070
but it ends in, you
know, printed out paper

379
00:17:47,070 --> 00:17:48,930
that if we ever lost curb power,

380
00:17:48,930 --> 00:17:52,230
we could turn the stack of
turtles back on the hard way.

381
00:17:52,230 --> 00:17:54,300
We've never had that, knock wood,

382
00:17:54,300 --> 00:17:56,343
but we do have a plan for that.

383
00:17:57,360 --> 00:17:59,400
And so that's what the
perimeter for encryption is.

384
00:17:59,400 --> 00:18:03,030
We call this pattern of unique DEKs

385
00:18:03,030 --> 00:18:07,020
that protect data with DEKs
that are then protected

386
00:18:07,020 --> 00:18:10,680
by a high order key, envelope encryption.

387
00:18:10,680 --> 00:18:14,520
And this is the way
all of it works at AWS,

388
00:18:14,520 --> 00:18:17,190
and this is the way you
should probably do it as well.

389
00:18:17,190 --> 00:18:19,620
And Jenn's gonna talk about
this idea of a key ring,

390
00:18:19,620 --> 00:18:22,410
about starting your own key hierarchy

391
00:18:22,410 --> 00:18:24,483
with a key that you get out of KMS.

392
00:18:29,700 --> 00:18:32,700
So that all sounds great.

393
00:18:32,700 --> 00:18:35,460
Now we know why customers care.

394
00:18:35,460 --> 00:18:37,500
We know what they're looking for

395
00:18:37,500 --> 00:18:38,730
and we kind of understand, okay,

396
00:18:38,730 --> 00:18:42,240
envelope encryption, how do you do it?

397
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:46,770
How should a customer let
you use their key material

398
00:18:46,770 --> 00:18:50,010
to integrate with your
software to protect their data

399
00:18:50,010 --> 00:18:51,723
that is in your hands?

400
00:18:53,130 --> 00:18:55,080
There's a couple simple ways to do this.

401
00:18:55,080 --> 00:18:57,810
If you're just writing objects into S3,

402
00:18:57,810 --> 00:18:59,510
just do cross account key sharing.

403
00:19:01,290 --> 00:19:02,123
End of list.

404
00:19:03,240 --> 00:19:07,140
But if you're holding
a multi-tenant database

405
00:19:07,140 --> 00:19:10,260
with individual customer records,

406
00:19:10,260 --> 00:19:12,960
it's a lot more complicated
than just give me the ARN.

407
00:19:14,220 --> 00:19:16,860
And depending on the nature of your ISV,

408
00:19:16,860 --> 00:19:19,470
if you've got your own data plane

409
00:19:19,470 --> 00:19:21,870
and it's not just a relational database

410
00:19:21,870 --> 00:19:24,750
but perhaps a much more complex data plane

411
00:19:24,750 --> 00:19:28,470
that is itself probably multi-tenant.

412
00:19:28,470 --> 00:19:32,130
Now you've got some very
interesting complexities,

413
00:19:32,130 --> 00:19:33,901
complexities around availability,

414
00:19:33,901 --> 00:19:36,900
complexities around persistence.

415
00:19:36,900 --> 00:19:38,700
'Cause the only thing
worse than losing data

416
00:19:38,700 --> 00:19:40,680
is losing a key 'cause losing a key

417
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:43,953
is like losing data, except even harder.

418
00:19:45,990 --> 00:19:48,290
So how do customers share
their keys with you?

419
00:19:49,410 --> 00:19:51,060
So there's three ways to do this.

420
00:19:51,960 --> 00:19:55,110
If what you're doing is
primarily just interacting

421
00:19:55,110 --> 00:19:59,010
with AWS resources, that is
to say you're not in the weeds

422
00:19:59,010 --> 00:20:01,470
of your own data plane and
a multi-tenant data plane.

423
00:20:01,470 --> 00:20:04,440
Just do it cross account resource sharing.

424
00:20:04,440 --> 00:20:07,050
It's one of the oldest
tricks from the IAM book.

425
00:20:07,050 --> 00:20:09,660
You write a resource policy
that goes on the key,

426
00:20:09,660 --> 00:20:11,523
we call that a key policy.

427
00:20:12,960 --> 00:20:17,280
And you delegate effectively,
a service principle

428
00:20:17,280 --> 00:20:20,310
that belongs to you, the ISV.

429
00:20:20,310 --> 00:20:24,930
So service.acmecorp.com

430
00:20:24,930 --> 00:20:28,980
is allowed to call for encrypt, decrypt,

431
00:20:28,980 --> 00:20:30,813
generate data key and describe key.

432
00:20:32,010 --> 00:20:33,870
That's the simplest part.

433
00:20:33,870 --> 00:20:35,370
Some customers think well

434
00:20:35,370 --> 00:20:37,560
or some ISVs think "Well
no, what I really want,

435
00:20:37,560 --> 00:20:40,420
what I really wanna do is
assume one of their roles

436
00:20:41,790 --> 00:20:44,490
and then use that to access the key."

437
00:20:44,490 --> 00:20:47,280
No, why would you do that? Don't do that.

438
00:20:47,280 --> 00:20:49,230
Just do cross account resource sharing.

439
00:20:50,190 --> 00:20:52,297
Now sometimes vendors are like,

440
00:20:52,297 --> 00:20:55,120
"Oh well I'll call this BYOK

441
00:20:57,180 --> 00:20:59,130
and I'll have all the key material

442
00:20:59,130 --> 00:21:02,130
and there's a key for Alice
and there's a key for Bob."

443
00:21:02,130 --> 00:21:04,983
But it's not really bring
your own key if you do that.

444
00:21:06,180 --> 00:21:07,740
Customers don't get the logging visibility

445
00:21:07,740 --> 00:21:08,573
that we talked about.

446
00:21:08,573 --> 00:21:09,406
They certainly don't get

447
00:21:09,406 --> 00:21:11,400
the big red button that we talked about.

448
00:21:11,400 --> 00:21:13,350
And so your customer's level of trust

449
00:21:13,350 --> 00:21:15,000
in the eventual solution that you're going

450
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:18,150
to market with can be greatly affected

451
00:21:18,150 --> 00:21:19,983
by the choices that you make here.

452
00:21:21,510 --> 00:21:25,770
We want you to be successful,
we really want our customers

453
00:21:25,770 --> 00:21:28,350
to be successful and you
guys are our customers.

454
00:21:28,350 --> 00:21:31,683
But often your customers are
also somehow our customers.

455
00:21:32,790 --> 00:21:34,500
And so we want you to
do this the right way,

456
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:36,550
which is why we're here having this talk.

457
00:21:37,680 --> 00:21:39,360
So as it turns out,
cross account key sharing

458
00:21:39,360 --> 00:21:40,660
is really straightforward.

459
00:21:41,850 --> 00:21:45,660
Resources on AWS have
their own policy document

460
00:21:45,660 --> 00:21:47,130
called a resource policy.

461
00:21:47,130 --> 00:21:48,570
And when you're talking about S3,

462
00:21:48,570 --> 00:21:51,420
it's often referred to as a bucket policy.

463
00:21:51,420 --> 00:21:54,120
If you're talking about KMS,
it's called a key policy.

464
00:21:54,960 --> 00:21:57,383
And as it turns out, this
is really straightforward.

465
00:21:58,320 --> 00:22:03,320
Statement, allow principle
that belongs to Acme Corp.

466
00:22:03,390 --> 00:22:06,660
Action, encrypt, decrypt,

467
00:22:06,660 --> 00:22:08,643
generate data key and describe key.

468
00:22:09,750 --> 00:22:11,200
Pretty straightforward stuff.

469
00:22:12,510 --> 00:22:15,090
It's key to understand, haha pun,

470
00:22:15,090 --> 00:22:17,250
it's essential to understand

471
00:22:17,250 --> 00:22:20,940
that you're only going to get authorized

472
00:22:20,940 --> 00:22:22,590
for the cryptographic operations.

473
00:22:24,270 --> 00:22:27,810
That you do not need and
nor should you ask for

474
00:22:27,810 --> 00:22:29,523
other actions on the key.

475
00:22:30,720 --> 00:22:34,623
Those ought to belong to the
key owner, your customer.

476
00:22:35,937 --> 00:22:37,890
'Cause some of those actions
could be really powerful.

477
00:22:37,890 --> 00:22:40,560
Disable does exactly what it sounds like.

478
00:22:40,560 --> 00:22:43,980
You don't need the ability to
call for disable on the key

479
00:22:43,980 --> 00:22:45,513
and you should not ask for it.

480
00:22:46,500 --> 00:22:48,390
There's a couple of other
very powerful actions.

481
00:22:48,390 --> 00:22:49,890
Put key policy.

482
00:22:49,890 --> 00:22:53,013
You do not need that and
nor should you ask for it.

483
00:22:53,880 --> 00:22:55,860
And perhaps most powerful of all,

484
00:22:55,860 --> 00:22:58,593
there's an API called
schedule key deletion.

485
00:22:59,580 --> 00:23:01,830
We don't actually let
you delete it right away

486
00:23:01,830 --> 00:23:04,020
'cause that's a very serious foot gun.

487
00:23:04,020 --> 00:23:06,810
But schedule key deletion,
you do not need it

488
00:23:06,810 --> 00:23:08,730
and you should not ask for it.

489
00:23:08,730 --> 00:23:11,010
All you need is very simple.

490
00:23:11,010 --> 00:23:13,290
Write on the key, encrypt, decrypt,

491
00:23:13,290 --> 00:23:15,123
generate data key and describe key.

492
00:23:17,100 --> 00:23:19,233
Now how do you get this going?

493
00:23:20,490 --> 00:23:24,123
How do you kind of bootstrap
this new customer onboarding?

494
00:23:24,990 --> 00:23:27,543
It's probably enough to
just publish some JSON.

495
00:23:28,380 --> 00:23:30,000
This is what it needs to look like.

496
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:31,893
Copy and paste it on your key policy.

497
00:23:32,820 --> 00:23:36,360
Your sales engineers can probably
do this for your customer

498
00:23:36,360 --> 00:23:39,093
during onboarding or ramping or whatever.

499
00:23:40,770 --> 00:23:43,650
You could probably give
them some cloud formation

500
00:23:43,650 --> 00:23:45,600
which would create a key

501
00:23:45,600 --> 00:23:47,400
and then put the right policy on it.

502
00:23:49,350 --> 00:23:51,567
And lots of other ways
to think about this.

503
00:23:51,567 --> 00:23:54,813
You wanna give 'em a terraform
thing? Sure, whatever.

504
00:23:55,920 --> 00:23:58,260
But you should be reasoning about this

505
00:23:58,260 --> 00:23:59,970
'cause it's essential that your customers

506
00:23:59,970 --> 00:24:02,220
not only get it right so they can start

507
00:24:02,220 --> 00:24:04,530
receiving the benefit of your software.

508
00:24:04,530 --> 00:24:06,330
It would be dumb to delay time to value

509
00:24:06,330 --> 00:24:08,400
just because it takes a week to figure out

510
00:24:08,400 --> 00:24:09,900
what to put on the key policy.

511
00:24:11,074 --> 00:24:13,320
